{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> χαλκ-εύς</b>, έως, ὁ: <br /> <i>plural</i> χαλκεῖς, <i>Attic dialect</i> <b>-ῆς</b>[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Aves” 490 (_anapaest meter_), 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 370d, _Epic dialect_ -ῆες (see. below): _accusative_ χαλκέας [prev. author] “Smp.” 221e, “R.” 428d, χαλκεῖς 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.214a \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>coppersmith,</b> opposed to τέκτων (joiner, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 370d), ἣν [ἀσπίδα] χ. ἤλασεν 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 12.295, etc.; μίτρη, τὴν χαλκῆες κάμον ἄνδρες 4.187, 216. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> generally, <b>worker in metal,</b> of a <b>goldsmith,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 3.432 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of a <b>worker in iron.</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 9.391 \">Refs</a>]; hence later, <b>blacksmith, smith</b> (χαλκέας τοὺς τὸν σίδηρον ἐργαζομένους [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Poetica” 1461a29), 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.68, Ar.[same place], 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 3.4.17; ἀνὴρ χ. 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 4.200; χ. χαλκοῦ καὶ σιδήρου LXX.Gen.4.22. \">LXX+5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>John Dory, Zeus faber,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-3rd c.AD: Oppianus Anazarbensis Epicus “Halieutica - Poetae Bucolici et Didactici” 1.133, probably in 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Historia Animalium” 535b18 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; distinguished from χαλκίς, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Athenaeus Epigrammaticus 7.328d. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]","strongNumber":"G5471","accentedUnicode":"χαλκεύς","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G5475","matchingForm":"χαλκός","stepTransliteration